post_text:
Good morning! We know that there were some technology issues that resulted in a lot of frustration yesterday, and we thank you for your flexibility and patience. We had some success with a software update last night that should help resolve issues with Zoom. However, we still have many student devices that are running without the update.

When the computers come online this morning, for those that have been updated, we are going to force a restart. For computers that have not been updated, we will push the update this morning, which may cause a disruption that will last about 5 minute. The download and installation will take about 2 or 3 minutes in the background, and you will receive a message that your computer will restart.

Students do have the ability to go into our Software Center and download the update. It will auto-install. This will allow you to do the update on your terms before classes get underway.

We know how difficult this is for our families and students, and we want to remove this obstacle as quickly as possible.

post_text: The July edition of East Bradford Neighbors Magazine features WCASD's Ashley Melanson who shares her experiencing teaching during the global pandemic. Mrs. Melanson was just named the new Elementary Instructional Technology Coordinator and will be based out of the Spellman Administration Building. She previously taught fourth grade at Westtown-Thornbury Elementary School. We are so proud of Mrs. Melanson and all of the dedicated WCASD teachers and staff who kept students engaged and connected during the shutdown.

West Chester Area School District tentatively plans to bring all students back to its schools this fall with a minimum of 3 feet separation (recommended by the World Health Organization, Bucks and Chester County Department of Health, and others.) Important information from the superintendent is on our website - https://www.wcasd.net/Domain/6199.

Task Force committees begin July 1 to look at a wide variety of implementation and feasibility issues.

The WC Cyber Program will be available for parents who aren't comfortable with the in-person plan. More information is available here - https://www.wcasd.net/Domain/6119

Please keep any comments respectful. Thank you.

We love our seniors!

Victoria,

We are so proud of the bright, caring and beautiful young woman you have become. It seems like only yesterday you were learning to walk at Gymboree with Katie, reading your favorite book Little Bird Biddle Bird before bed and performing at your first dance recital. We watched you learn to ride Roxy at Drakestown Equestrian, show courage and bravery when we moved to Pennsylvania and beamed with pride when you moved up to high heeled tap shoes. Now you have learned to drive and you are graduating High School.

We are so excited for you to start this next chapter in your life. No matter what you choose to do or where life takes you remember to always be true to yourself. To quote our favorite Dr. Seuss book ‚ÄúYou‚Äôre off to great places! Today is your day! Your mountain is waiting so get on your way!‚Äù

We love you so much!
Mommy and Daddy

post_text:
We love our seniors!

To our son, Shane, we wish only the best of everything. This year‚Äôs graduation may not be what anyone expected, but it is certainly unique and that is certainly representative of you! You have always been a curious kid and loved to learn about all sorts of things. You have always been a kind and caring person. We loved watching you explore new things whether it was in Boy Scouts, or learning to play the violin and the piano, or playing baseball, soccer, golf or snowboarding! You were self-taught in many things that you found interesting and wanted to research, including your love of astronomy and telescopes which is leading to your next step to study Astronomy and Astrophysics at Penn State. We learn something new from you every day ourselves! Our warmest thoughts and highest hopes are with you as we celebrate your graduation. Always remember, there is no limit to what you can achieve. You have a bright future ahead of you and we can‚Äôt wait to see all that you achieve. We are and will always be so very proud of you!

post_text:
We love our seniors!

To Pete Nelson and the Class of 2020, aka Senior Skip Day Champs,
For everything, there is a season. Go ahead and cry and mourn for the things you missed out on but don‚Äôt forget to laugh and dance as well. The human mind can‚Äôt even fathom the things God has prepared.

The world will continue to change‚Äîsometimes too fast and sometimes not fast enough. But the truest things--they still remain true even when the dust settles.

What is the truest thing you know? Uncertainty can be scary but rest assured, your future is still bright and still lies ahead of you. It may be slightly delayed but it‚Äôs still there and will still work out the way it‚Äôs meant to be. Hold onto the truest thing you know.

God bless the class of 2020!

post_text: The West Chester Area School District mourns the sudden death of Stetson Middle School Principal Dr. Charles Cognato. "Dr. C.," as he was affectionately known, was a kind, caring educator who loved the students and families with whom he worked. He was taken too soon, and he will be greatly missed. Please email any photos/memories of Dr. C you'd like to share, to communicationsdept@wcasd.net as we begin to compile a tribute.

Know that you are loved unconditionally and that we will always be here for you!

Love,

We love our seniors!

Wow! From this photo in the fall to now, who would have thought your senior year would have ended like this? Hard to believe it's finally here. Always be the kind-hearted person you are. One that would do anything got those who are around you. Try to do what is right and not what is easy! We all believe you'll make the best of your college career and take on life at full speed. Can't wait to learn more things from you and watch you become the best version of yourself! We can only imagine what kind of projects you will get into next.

We love you more than you know, and we are so very proud of you!

Dad, Mom, Kristen, and Lindsey

post_text:
We love our seniors!

Jamie,

We are so proud of the young man and musician that you have become. From the initial days of gritting our teeth while listening to you practice so you could earn your belts on recorder to these past years watching you perform both on the field and at WCU, we could not be prouder or more amazed at seeing just how far you have progressed and what a truly fantastic performer and man you have become. I am so sorry that your final senior performances have been taken from you, all of the milestone *things* that you and your peers should have been able to experience. Instead of focusing on what has been missed, continue to look forward to all the new performances you will have as you move on to college and the future that lies ahead for you. The new fields and stages that you will grace. We look forward to seeing you continue to grow into an even better performer and kind, generous, giving man than you already are.

Love you more!

Mom and Dad

post_text:
This Memorial Day doesn't afford us the opportunity to honor our fallen veterans in ways that we typically would, but as a District, we salute them and thank them for their service and the ultimate sacrifice for our freedom.

The following video message includes information about how our school district is celebrating our graduating seniors; how we're continuing to plan for a number of scenarios for the opening of school in the fall; and how we'll be offering a new cyber program for grades 6 through 12. I hope you'll find a moment to watch this message and to remember the sacrifices of our veterans. I also hope this note finds you and your family doing well. I know this has been a very difficult time.

Thanks for your support for our students and schools, and please don't hesitate to contact me with questions.

-Dr. Jim Scanlon

post_text:
We love our seniors!

"Dear Karis,

We are so proud of all of your accomplishments! There is nothing that you set your mind to that you did not accomplish: From National Honor Society member to State Long Jump Qualifier, to YMCA Gymnastics All-American, to college scholarship recipient. But, more than your accomplishments, we are proud of who you have become as a person. You have invested in the lives of others through the way that you have volunteered giving your summers away to the Young Life work crew, and your Old Mill, the way you love your friends and family, the way that you have stood by your convictions, and the way that you have honored us are your parents. You, youngest of 7, social butterfly, opinionated, God-fearing, kind-hearted, fun-loving, ex-homeschooler, are a joy to us! We love you tons!

Trust in the Lord with all your heart, and lean not on your own understanding; in all your ways acknowledge him, and he will make your paths straight. Prov.3:5-6"

Love,
Dad & Mom

post_text: America's favorite neighbor, Mr. Rogers, regularly used 1-4-3 as his special code for "I Love You" - based on the number of letters in each word. In Pennsylvania, the 143rd day of the year is Fred Roger's Day #143DayinPA. A day for PA residents to share the acts of kindness and good deeds they do for each other.

post_text:
We love our seniors!

"Dear Annabel,

Congratulations on your graduation from high school! We are so incredibly proud of you. You have worked so hard to achieve your high school goals. Your next chapter will be just as amazing, and we will continue to cheer you on. Your work ethic and good heart will allow you to achieve your next goal. Your laugh and smile are contagious. You make it easy to be your parents! You have shown us that you are now an adult who makes good choices, learns from mistakes, and follows your passions. We cannot wait to follow you through your journey at Widener University. As you begin your studies in nursing this fall, know that you are not only working towards your career, but you are gaining a world full of gratitude for choosing it."

We love you so very much!

Love your family,

Mom, Dana, Ryan, Jake, and Sammy

post_text:
Congratulations to Sophia Hofmann, a fourth-grade student at Starkweather Elementary School for placing second in EngineerGirl's 2020 Writing Contest. EngineerGirl, a program of the National Academy of Engineering, is designed to bring national attention to the exciting opportunities that engineering represents for girls and women.

Click on the photo to read Sophia's winning entry. Great job, Sophia!
